  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "And so the framework we propose differs from Watzl's in two key respects.",
    "2 First, while we agree with Watzl that a full theory of the ethics of attention should explain how prudential, epistemic, and other non-moral norms interact with moral ones (Watzl, 2022, p. 90), we treat such questions as secondary.",
    "This is because attention allocation can be morally good or bad independently of whether it satisfies other kinds of norms.",
    "Spying on your ex, for instance, can be epistemically good in that it can justify your belief that she's now dating that \"friend\" of hers you always suspected.",
    "And reading leaked emails to engage in insider trading can be prudentially good in that it can promote your own financial interests."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "2 First, while we agree with Watzl that a full theory of the ethics of attention should explain how prudential, epistemic, and other non-moral norms interact with moral ones (Watzl, 2022, p. 90), we treat such questions as secondary."
